<section xml:id="recursive-methods_vocabulary">
<title>Vocabulary</title>
<ul>
<li>
<title>iterative:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>iterative</h></idx>
A method or algorithm that repeats steps by using one or more loops.</p></li>
<li>
<title>recursive:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>recursive</h></idx>
A method or algorithm that invokes itself one or more times with different arguments.</p></li>
<li>
<title>base case:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>base case</h></idx>
A condition that causes a recursive method <em>not</em> to make another recursive call.</p></li>
<li>
<title>factorial:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>factorial</h></idx>
The product of all the integers up to and including a given integer.</p></li>
<li>
<title>leap of faith:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>leap of faith</h></idx>
A way to read recursive programs by assuming that the recursive call works, rather than following the flow of execution.</p></li>
<li>
<title>binary:</title>
<p>
<idx><h>binary</h></idx>
A system that uses only zeros and ones to represent numbers.
Also known as <q>base 2</q>.</p></li>
</ul>
</section>
